{"title_page": "Mudbir al-Far'un", "text_new": "{{Infobox governor\n| office = [[Tribal chief]] of the al-Fatlah tribe\n| term_start = unknown\n| term_end = September 1918\n| predecessor = unknown\n| successor = 'Mujbil al Fara'un\n| blank1 = Siblings\n| data1 = 'Mujbil al Fara'un\n| blank2 = Tribe\n| data2 = al-Fatlah tribe\n| battles = 1913 Euphrates rebellion\n| death_date = September 1918\n| death_place = [[Ottoman Iraq]]\n}}\n'''Mudbir al-Far'un'''{{Refn|Mudbir al-Far'un is the transliteration used by Keiko Sakai in ''Political parties and social networks in Iraq''.<ref name=\"Keiko1994\"/> Other transliterations used include Mibdir al Fir\u2019awn<ref name=\"Haddad\"/>, Mubdir al Fir'un<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/109051.pdf|title=The Political, Intellectual and Social Roots of the Iraqi Independence Movement 1920.|last=Nadhmi|first=W.|date=1974|website=core.ac.uk|page=77|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, and simply \"Madbir\".<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\"/>|name=transliteration|group=note}} (d. 1918) was a chieftain of the al-Fatlah tribe who led a rebellion against the Ottoman Empire in 1913.\n\n== 1913 Euphrates rebellion ==\nIn 1913, Mudbir addressed a tribal gathering in [[Diwaniyah]], lamenting Ottoman rule:<ref name=\"Haddad\">{{Cite journal|last=Haddad|first=Fanar|date=2012|title=Political Awakenings in an Artificial State: Iraq, 1914-20|url=https://www.academia.edu/4275183/Political_Awakenings_in_an_Artificial_State_Iraq_1914-20|journal=International Journal of Contemporary Iraqi Studies|language=en|volume=|pages=6, 7|via=}}</ref>  \n\n{{Quote|text=Sirs, we used to meet [\u2026] and discuss the fate of our land/country [''bila-dona''] in which lived our fathers and grandfathers proudly [\u2026] Sirs, God created people and chose from amongst them the Arabs, and chose from the Arabs Quraysh, and from Quraysh He chose Hashim, and He chose from Hashim our Prophet Muhammad, praise be upon him, and He made him the Prophet of Islam; that religion that He chose for this nation and [for which] He revealed the Koran in the Arabic language which is the language of your fathers and grandfathers. Therefore you are the best of nations in the world [\u2026] Yes! Why do you bow to foreign [non-Arab, Turkish] rule controlling you with you under its mercy like slaves?|author=Mudbir al-Far'un|title=1913 speech|source=}}\n\nSubsequently, rebels led by Mudbir clashed with Ottoman forces throughout the mid-[[Euphrates]] region of Mesopotamia. Although this rebellion ended in failure, Mudbir would continue to be the al-Fatlah chieftain.\n\n== Role in the First World War ==\nIn 1914, the Ottoman Empire called upon various chieftains to aid them in a [[Jihad]] against the British Empire. Mudbir al-Far'un was unwilling to answer the call, as he believed the Ottomans would not be able to emerge victorious against the superior British forces in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"Keiko1994\">{{Cite web|url=http://etheses.dur.ac.uk/5105/1/5105_2558.PDF?UkUDh:CyT|title=Political parties and social networks in Iraq, 1908-1920|last=Sakai|first=Keiko|date=1994|website=etheses.dur.ac.uk|page=57|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Death and succession ==\nMudbir died in September 1918.<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\" /> He was succeeded by his brother, 'Mujbil al Fara'un.<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\">{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/109051.pdf|title=The Political, Intellectual and Social Roots of the Iraqi Independence Movement 1920.|last=Nadhmi|first=W.|date=1974|website=core.ac.uk|page=336|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> British records note that Mujbil was \"very useful to us immediately after the occupation\"<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Arab rebels]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rebels of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox governor\n| office = [[Tribal chief]] of the al-Fatlah tribe\n| term_start = unknown\n| term_end = September 1918\n| predecessor = unknown\n| successor = 'Mujbil al Fara'un\n| blank1 = Siblings\n| data1 = 'Mujbil al Fara'un\n| blank2 = Tribe\n| data2 = al-Fatlah tribe\n| battles = 1913 Euphrates rebellion\n| death_date = September 1918\n| death_place = [[Ottoman Iraq]]\n}}\n'''Mudbir al-Far'un'''{{Refn|Mudbir al-Far'un is the transliteration used by Keiko Sakai in ''Political parties and social networks in Iraq''.<ref name=\"Keiko1994\"/> Other transliterations used include Mibdir al Fir\u2019awn<ref name=\"Haddad\"/>, Mubdir al Fir'un<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/109051.pdf|title=The Political, Intellectual and Social Roots of the Iraqi Independence Movement 1920.|last=Nadhmi|first=W.|date=1974|website=core.ac.uk|page=77|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, and simply \"Madbir\"<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\"/>|name=transliteration|group=note}} (d. 1918) was a chieftain of the al-Fatlah tribe who led a rebellion against the Ottoman Empire in 1913.\n\n== 1913 Euphrates rebellion ==\nIn 1913, Mudbir addressed a tribal gathering in [[Diwaniyah]], lamenting Ottoman rule:<ref name=\"Haddad\">{{Cite journal|last=Haddad|first=Fanar|date=2012|title=Political Awakenings in an Artificial State: Iraq, 1914-20|url=https://www.academia.edu/4275183/Political_Awakenings_in_an_Artificial_State_Iraq_1914-20|journal=International Journal of Contemporary Iraqi Studies|language=en|volume=|pages=6, 7|via=}}</ref>  \n\n{{Quote|text=Sirs, we used to meet [\u2026] and discuss the fate of our land/country [''bila-dona''] in which lived our fathers and grandfathers proudly [\u2026] Sirs, God created people and chose from amongst them the Arabs, and chose from the Arabs Quraysh, and from Quraysh He chose Hashim, and He chose from Hashim our Prophet Muhammad, praise be upon him, and He made him the Prophet of Islam; that religion that He chose for this nation and [for which] He revealed the Koran in the Arabic language which is the language of your fathers and grandfathers. Therefore you are the best of nations in the world [\u2026] Yes! Why do you bow to foreign [non-Arab, Turkish] rule controlling you with you under its mercy like slaves?|author=Mudbir al-Far'un|title=1913 speech|source=}}\n\nSubsequently, rebels led by Mudbir clashed with Ottoman forces throughout the mid-[[Euphrates]] region of Mesopotamia. Although this rebellion ended in failure, Mudbir would continue to be the al-Fatlah chieftain.\n\n== Role in the First World War ==\nIn 1914, the Ottoman Empire called upon various chieftains to aid them in a [[Jihad]] against the British Empire. Mudbir al-Far'un was unwilling to answer the call, as he believed the Ottomans would not be able to emerge victorious against the superior British forces in [[World War I]].<ref name=\"Keiko1994\">{{Cite web|url=http://etheses.dur.ac.uk/5105/1/5105_2558.PDF?UkUDh:CyT|title=Political parties and social networks in Iraq, 1908-1920|last=Sakai|first=Keiko|date=1994|website=etheses.dur.ac.uk|page=57|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Death and succession ==\nMudbir died in September 1918.<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\" /> He was succeeded by his brother, 'Mujbil al Fara'un.<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\">{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/109051.pdf|title=The Political, Intellectual and Social Roots of the Iraqi Independence Movement 1920.|last=Nadhmi|first=W.|date=1974|website=core.ac.uk|page=336|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> British records note that Mujbil was \"very useful to us immediately after the occupation\"<ref name=\"Nadhmi1974page336\" />\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Arab rebels]]\n[[Category:1918 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rebels of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "Koopinator", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mudbir_al-Far%27un"}
{"title_page": "Beau Blankenship", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = Beau Blankenship\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| number              = --\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1990|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[Norman, Oklahoma]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 9\n| weight_lbs          = 202\n| high_school          = [[Norman North High School|Norman North (OK) Norman]]\n| college             = [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| undraftedyear       = 2014\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})*\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n| highlights          = \n* [[Independence Bowl]] Co-Offensive MVP (2012)\n* Second-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2012)\n\nVP (2012)\n* independence bowl rushing touchdown Record \n* Second-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2012)\n*Phill Steele 1st team all Mac 2012 \n*sports illustrated mid-season all American 2012 \n\n| nflnew              = \n}}\n\n'''Beau Blankenship''' (born August 13, 1990) is a former [[American football]] [[running back]]. He was signed by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2014. He played [[college football]] at [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State]] in 2009 and [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]] from 2011 to 2013.\n\n==High school==\nBlankenship played football for [[Norman North High School]], where he gained 5,050 rushing yards and 59 total [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=\"Ohio\">[http://www.ohiobobcats.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/beau_blankenship_764978.html \"Beau Blankenship Profile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102235230/http://www.ohiobobcats.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/beau_blankenship_764978.html |date=2013-01-02 }}. ohiobobcats.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref> He was an all-state selection. Blankenship was also on the track and field team.<ref>[http://www.cyclones.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10700&ATCLID=3662167 \"Beau Blankenship\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818142905/http://www.cyclones.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10700&ATCLID=3662167 |date=2012-08-18 }}. cyclones.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n==College==\nIn 2009, Blankenship played seven games for Iowa State. He gained 11 total yards. He then redshirted in 2010. In 2011, he played 13 games for Ohio and had 462 rushing yards and four touchdowns.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> He had a season-high 129 yards against [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] on November 10. He rushed for 47 yards in the [[2011 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl]].<ref>[http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/gamelog/_/id/480702/year/2011/beau-blankenship \"Beau Blankenship Game By Game Stats and Performance\"]. espn.go.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Blankenship rushed for 1,604 yards and 15 touchdowns, breaking [[Kalvin McRae]]'s Ohio record for rushing yards in a season.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> On September 29, against [[UMass Minutemen football|Massachusetts]], Blankenship had 43 carries, which tied a school record; his 269 yards in that game was a season high for him. In the [[2012 Independence Bowl]], he totaled 104 rushing yards, and his four touchdowns set an Independence Bowl record. It was Blankenship's ninth 100-yard rushing game in 2012, which was another school record. He was also named the game's co-offensive most valuable player. Blankenship was named to the 2012 All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] second team.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> His 312 rushing attempts led the MAC, and his 1,604 rushing yards ranked second.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/beau-blankenship-1.html \"Beau Blankenship Stats\"]. sports-reference.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Season !! rowspan=2|Team !! colspan=6|Rushing !! colspan=5|Receiving\n|-\n ! GP !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD \n|-\n ! ~[[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] !! [[2009 Iowa State Cyclones football team|Iowa State]]\n | 7 || 4 || 11 || 2.8 || 5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n ! ~[[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]] !! [[2011 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio University]]\n | 13 || 93 || 462 || 5.0 || 48 || 4 || 3 || 19 || 6.3 || 11 || 0 \n|-\n ! ~[[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] !! [[2012 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio University]]\n | 13 || 312 || 1604 || 5.1 || 58 || 15 || 21 || 182 || 8.7 || 28 || 1 \n|-\n! ~[[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio University]]\n | 13 || 204 || 910 || 4.5 || 53 || 5 || 15 || 62 || 4.1 || 10 || 0 \n|-\n! || Total\n! 46 || 613 || 2987 || 4.9 || 58 || 24 || 39 || 263 || 6.7 || 28 || 1 \n|}\n~includes bowl game\n\n==Professional career==\nFollowing an invitation to rookie minicamp, the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] signed Blankenship on May 17, 2014. He was released on July 23.\n\nBeau currently owns a Real estate brokerage (Engel & V\u00f6lkers 30-A beaches) on scenic highway 30-A. and a property management company owner in Santa Rosa Beach, FL. [http://www.davisprop.com/agents/beau-blankenship/ Source]\n\n==Personal life==\nBlankenship is a communication studies major. He was born to Cynthia and Charlie on August 13, 1990, and has one sister, Brittany.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blankenship, Beau}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Norman, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American football running backs]]\n[[Category:Iowa State Cyclones football players]]\n[[Category:Ohio University alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio Bobcats football players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL player\n| name                = Beau Blankenship\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| number              = --\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1990|8|13}}\n| birth_place         = [[Norman, Oklahoma]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 9\n| weight_lbs          = 202\n| high_school          = [[Norman North High School|Norman North (OK) Norman]]\n| college             = [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]]\n| undraftedyear       = 2014\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})*\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n| highlights          = \n* [[Independence Bowl]] Co-Offensive MVP (2012)\n* Second-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2012)\n\nVP (2012)\n* independence bowl rushing touchdown Record \n* Second-team All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] (2012)\n*Phill Steele 1st team all Mac 2012 \n*sports illustrated mid-season all American 2012 \n\n| nflnew              = \n}}\n\n'''Beau Blankenship''' (born August 13, 1990) is a former [[American football]] [[running back]]. He was signed by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2014. He played [[college football]] at [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State]] in 2009 and [[Ohio Bobcats football|Ohio]] from 2011 to 2013.\n\n==High school==\nBlankenship played football for [[Norman North High School]], where he gained 5,050 rushing yards and 59 total [[touchdown]]s.<ref name=\"Ohio\">[http://www.ohiobobcats.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/beau_blankenship_764978.html \"Beau Blankenship Profile\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130102235230/http://www.ohiobobcats.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/beau_blankenship_764978.html |date=2013-01-02 }}. ohiobobcats.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref> He was an all-state selection. Blankenship was also on the track and field team.<ref>[http://www.cyclones.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10700&ATCLID=3662167 \"Beau Blankenship\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818142905/http://www.cyclones.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10700&ATCLID=3662167 |date=2012-08-18 }}. cyclones.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n==College==\nIn 2009, Blankenship played seven games for Iowa State. He gained 11 total yards. He then redshirted in 2010. In 2011, he played 13 games for Ohio and had 462 rushing yards and four touchdowns.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> He had a season-high 129 yards against [[Central Michigan Chippewas football|Central Michigan]] on November 10. He rushed for 47 yards in the [[2011 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl]].<ref>[http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/gamelog/_/id/480702/year/2011/beau-blankenship \"Beau Blankenship Game By Game Stats and Performance\"]. espn.go.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Blankenship rushed for 1,604 yards and 15 touchdowns, breaking [[Kalvin McRae]]'s Ohio record for rushing yards in a season.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> On September 29, against [[UMass Minutemen football|Massachusetts]], Blankenship had 43 carries, which tied a school record; his 269 yards in that game was a season high for him. In the [[2012 Independence Bowl]], he totaled 104 rushing yards, and his four touchdowns set an Independence Bowl record. It was Blankenship's ninth 100-yard rushing game in 2012, which was another school record. He was also named the game's co-offensive most valuable player. Blankenship was named to the 2012 All-[[Mid-American Conference|MAC]] second team.<ref name=\"Ohio\"/> His 312 rushing attempts led the MAC, and his 1,604 rushing yards ranked second.<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/beau-blankenship-1.html \"Beau Blankenship Stats\"]. sports-reference.com. Retrieved February 2, 2013.</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n ! rowspan=2|Season !! rowspan=2|Team !! col