{"title_page": "Reynosa", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Reynosa\n|native_name            = <small>''Villa de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe de Reynosa''<small>\n|nickname               = Metr\u00f3polis industrial de Tamaulipas\n|motto                  = ''Trabajar por la patria es forjar nuestro destino''<br />(To work for the motherland is to forge our destiny)\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|image_seal             = Escudoreynosa.jpg\n|image_shield           =\n|image_map              = Reynosa, TM-map.svg\n|mapsize                = 150px\n|map_caption            = Location of Reynosa within Tamaulipas\n|image_map1             = Mexico map, MX-TAM.svg\n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = Location of Tamaulipas within Mexico\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Mexico}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[States of Mexico|State]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Tamaulipas}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Political divisions of Mexico|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Reynosa Municipality]]\n|government_type        = \n|leader_title           = [[List of presidents of Reynosa Municipality|Mayor]]\n|leader_name            = [[Maki Esther Ortiz Dom\u00ednguez]] <br/>(2016\u2013present) ({{PAN party}} {{PRD party}} {{MC party}})\n|leader_title1          =  \n|leader_name1           = \n|leader_title2          =\n|leader_name2           =\n|leader_title3          =\n|leader_name3           = \n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 14 March, 1749\n|established_title2     = Founded as\n|established_date2      = ''Villa de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe de Reinosa''\n|established_title3     = \n|established_date3      = \n|founder                = Carlos Cant\u00fa Gonz\u00e1lez\n|area_magnitude         = \n|area_total_km2         = 3,156.34 sq kilometers\n|area_total_sq_mi       = 1218.66 sq. miles\n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_land_sq_mi        = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|area_water_sq_mi       = \n|area_water_percent     = \n|area_urban_km2          = \n|area_urban_sq_mi       = \n|area_metro_km2         = \n|area_metro_sq_mi       = \n|population_as_of       = 2012\n|population_note        = \n|population_total       = 612,183<ref name=\"Mexico Census\">{{cite web|title=Mexico Census|url=http://www.inegi.org.mx/sistemas/consulta_resultados/iter2010.aspx?c=27329&s=est|publisher=Instituto Nacional de Estadistica y Geografia}}</ref> \n|population_density_km2         = \n|population_density_sq_mi       = \n|population_metro               = 1,500,000 \n|population_density_metro_km2   = \n|population_density_metro_sq_mi =\n|population_urban       = 725,793 \n|timezone               = [[Central Standard Time|CST]]\n|utc_offset             = \u22126 \n|timezone_DST           = [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = \u22125\n|coordinates            = {{coord|26|05|32|N|98|16|40|W|region:MX|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m              = 33\n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = 88500\n|website                = [http://www.reynosa.gob.mx www.reynosa.gob.mx]\n|footnotes              = Area Code          899\n'''Airport'''  <br /> [[General Lucio Blanco International Airport]]\n'''Airport Code''' <br /> REX\n}}\n'''Reynosa''' ({{IPA-es|rei\u02c8nosa}}) is a border city in the northern part of the state of [[Tamaulipas]], in [[Mexico]]. It is also the municipal seat of [[Reynosa Municipality]].\n\nThe city is located on the southern bank of the [[Rio Grande]] in the international [[Reynosa\u2013McAllen Metropolitan Area]], directly across of the [[Mexico-U.S. border]] from [[Hidalgo, Texas]]. \n\nAs of 2013, the city of Reynosa has a population of 672,183.<ref name=\"Mexico Census\"/>   If the [[floating population]] is included in the census count, the population can reach up to approximately 1,000,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=INEGI cont\u00f3 mal en Reynosa: Alcalde|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/notas/31372/INEGI-conto-mal-en-Reynosa-Alcalde.html|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nReynosa was founded on 14 March 1749 with 297 inhabitants by Carlos Cant\u00fa under the command of [[Jos\u00e9 de Escand\u00f3n y Helguera]] the Count of [[Sierra Gorda]]. But due to flooding in the area on the 4 July 1802, they decided to move five miles to the east keeping the same margin between them and the Rio Grande. It was not until 1926 that the state government recognized Reynosa as a city.\n\nReynosa was first named ''Villa de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe de Reinosa''. The pioneers of the Villa proceeded from El Nuevo Reino de Le\u00f3n, especially from Monterrey, Cadereyta, Cerralvo and El Pil\u00f3n. The town was composed of 50 families. It was given the name of Reynosa as a tribute to the [[Reinosa|town with the same name]] in Spain, the birthplace of the [[Viceroyalties of the Spanish Empire|Viceroy]] [[Juan Francisco de G\u00fcemes, 1st Count of Revillagigedo|de G\u00fcemes y Horcasitas]].\n\n===Current===\nReynosa extends across 3,156.34 sq kilometers (1218.66 sq. miles), representing 3.7 per cent of the [[Tamaulipas]] territory. Today it is the location of several satellite U.S. companies doing business to take advantage of low labor rates and industry incentives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cfomaquiladoras.org/serieglobalizacion.en.html |title=Four-part series on globalization |publisher=Cfomaquiladoras.org |accessdate=2012-02-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222214105/http://www.cfomaquiladoras.org/serieglobalizacion.en.html |archive-date=2012-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2012, an explosion at the nearby [[Pemex]] gas plant killed 30 and injured 46 people. Pemex Director Juan Jose Suarez said that there was \"no evidence that it was a deliberate incident, or some kind of attack\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican Tamaulipas state gas plant blast kills 26|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19645529|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=19 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico probes Pemex gas plant explosion which killed 26|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19655901|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19670668 | work=BBC News | title=Blast at Pemex gas plant in Mexico claims more lives | date=20 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was described as a major hotspot in the [[Mexican Drug War]], as a result of the internecine wars between the [[Gulf_Cartel|Gulf]] and [[Los Zetas]] drugs cartels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/world-us-canada-40755559/trump-s-wall-on-patrol-in-the-border-s-deadliest-town|title=US-Mexico border's most dangerous town|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nReynosa is the largest and most populous city in the state of Tamaulipas, followed by [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Ciudad Victoria]], [[Tampico]], and [[R\u00edo Bravo, Tamaulipas|R\u00edo Bravo]]. In addition, the international [[Reynosa\u2013McAllen Metropolitan Area]] counts with a population of 1,500,000 inhabitants,<ref>{{cite web|title=McAllen Overview|url=http://www.mcallen.org/Business-Community/McAllen-Overview|publisher=McAllen Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=America: metropolitan areas (McAllen-Reynosa)|url=http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=32&geo=-2&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&pt=a&va=x|publisher=World Gazetteer|accessdate=13 November 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001090654/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=32&geo=-2&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&pt=a&va=x|archivedate=2007-10-01}}</ref> making it the [[Metropolitan areas of Mexico|third largest metropolitan area]] in the Mexico\u2013U.S. border after [[San Diego\u2013Tijuana]] and [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez]]. Reynosa is the [[List of cities in Mexico|30th largest city]] in Mexico and anchors the largest metropolitan area in Tamaulipas.\n\nIn 2011, Reynosa was the fastest growing city in the state of Tamaulipas, and was among the top five fastest growing cities in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Hidalgo, Texas|url=http://www.hidalgotexas.com/cityprofile.pdf|publisher=Profile of Hidalgo, Texas|accessdate=3 November 2011}}</ref> \n\nThe city is about {{convert|11|mi|km}} south of [[McAllen, Texas]].<ref>Sanchez, Claudio. \"[https://www.npr.org/2014/09/11/347392083/child-migrants-settle-uneasily-in-the-big-easy Child Migrants Settle Uneasily In The Big Easy]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6bMCsr7w4?url=http://www.npr.org/2014/09/11/347392083/child-migrants-settle-uneasily-in-the-big-easy Archive]). [[National Public Radio]]. September 11, 2014. Retrieved on September 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nReynosa has a [[semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Bsh'') with short, mild winters and hot summers.<ref name=encmuc>{{cite web | url = http://www.e-local.gob.mx/work/templates/enciclo/EMM28tamaulipas/municipios/20832a.html | title = Cozumel | publisher = Secretar\u00eda de Gobernaci\u00f3n | work = Enciclopedia de los Municipios de M\u00e9xico | language = Spanish | accessdate = April 13, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nWinters are mild and dry with a January high of {{convert|22|C|F|0}} and a low of {{convert|11|C|F|0}} although temperatures can fall below {{convert|10|C|F|0}}.<ref name = encmuc /> Summers are hot with a July mean of {{convert|30|C|F|0}} and temperatures can exceed {{convert|40|C|F|0}} anytime from May until August.<ref name = encmuc/> The average annual precipitation is {{convert|452|mm|in|0}}, with most of it being concentrated in the summer months though the months May and June are the wettest. \n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Reynosa (1951\u20132010)\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 35.0\n|Feb record high C = 38.0\n|Mar record high C = 44.0\n|Apr record high C = 42.0\n|May record high C = 43.0\n|Jun record high C = 42.0\n|Jul record high C = 43.0\n|Aug record high C = 42.0\n|Sep record high C = 40.0\n|Oct record high C = 39.0\n|Nov record high C = 38.0\n|Dec record high C = 36.0\n|Jan high C = 21.9\n|Feb high C = 24.5\n|Mar high C = 29.1\n|Apr high C = 31.8\n|May high C = 34.3\n|Jun high C = 36.7\n|Jul high C = 36.9\n|Aug high C = 36.6\n|Sep high C = 35.0\n|Oct high C = 31.0\n|Nov high C = 26.7\n|Dec high C = 23.0\n|year high C = 30.6\n|Jan mean C = 16.2\n|Feb mean C = 18.4\n|Mar mean C = 21.9\n|Apr mean C = 24.8\n|May mean C = 27.6\n|Jun mean C = 29.5\n|Jul mean C = 29.9\n|Aug mean C = 29.8\n|Sep mean C = 28.1\n|Oct mean C = 24.6\n|Nov mean C = 20.6\n|Dec mean C = 17.3\n|year mean C = 24.1\n|Jan low C = 10.6\n|Feb low C = 12.3\n|Mar low C = 14.8\n|Apr low C = 17.7\n|May low C = 21.0\n|Jun low C = 22.2\n|Jul low C = 22.8\n|Aug low C = 23.0\n|Sep low C = 21.2\n|Oct low C = 18.3\n|Nov low C = 14.5\n|Dec low C = 11.6\n|year low C = 17.5\n|Jan record low C = -2.0\n|Feb record low C = -4.0\n|Mar record low C = 2.0\n|Apr record low C = 7.5\n|May record low C = 10.0\n|Jun record low C = 12.0\n|Jul record low C = 17.0\n|Aug record low C = 14.0\n|Sep record low C = 13.0\n|Oct record low C = 8.0\n|Nov record low C = 0.0\n|Dec record low C = -7.0\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 14.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 12.6\n|Mar precipitation mm = 7.3\n|Apr precipitation mm = 24.8\n|May precipitation mm = 73.0\n|Jun precipitation mm = 99.7\n|Jul precipitation mm = 24.3\n|Aug precipitation mm = 67.4\n|Sep precipitation mm = 72.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 27.4\n|Nov precipitation mm = 11.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 16.9\n|year precipitation mm = 452.5\n|source 1 = Servicio Meteorologico Nacional<ref name=SMN>[http://smn.cna.gob.mx/climatologia/Normales5110/NORMAL28079.TXT NORMALES CLIMATOL\u00d3GICAS 1951\u20132010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517154247/http://smn.cna.gob.mx/climatologia/Normales5110/NORMAL28079.TXT |date=2014-05-17 }} (in Spanish) National Meteorological Service of Mexico. Retrieved September 30, 2012.</ref>\n|date=September 2012\n}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Abraham Ancer]] \u2013 Professional Golfer\n*[[Xavier Baez]] \u2013 Footballer\n*[[Jorge Cantu]] \u2013 Major League Baseball player\n*[[Christian Ch\u00e1vez]] \u2013 Singer and actor\n*[[Laura Flores]] \u2013 Actress, hostess and singer\n*[[Jaime Garc\u00eda (baseball)|Jaime Garcia]] \u2013 Major League Baseball player\n*[[N\u00e9stor Garza]] \u2013 Former WBA World Super Bantamweight Champion\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Cant\u00fa Garza]] \u2013 Geneticist\n*[[Vidal Medina]] \u2013 Playwright and theatre director\n*[[Maki Esther Ortiz]] - Senator\n*[[Los Rel\u00e1mpagos del Norte]] - Musical duo\n*[[Komander]] - Wrestler\n*[[Ashty Edith Duncan]] - songwriter\n*[[Beto Quintanilla]] - Artist\n\n==Transportation==\nReynosa is served by the [[General Lucio Blanco International Airport]], which has flights to multiple important Mexican cities on six airlines, some serving it with aircraft such as [[Boeing 737]] and [[Airbus A320]].\n\nIn addition, the [[McAllen Miller International Airport]] in [[McAllen, Texas]], is also relatively close and is served by airlines like [[Allegiant Air]], [[American Airlines|American]] and [[United Airlines|United]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Broughton, Chad|title=Boom, Bust, Exodus: The Rust Belt, the Maquilas, and a Tale of Two Cities|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0199765614 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Boom_Bust_Exodus_The_Rust_Belt_the_Maqui.html?id=PWc3BQAAQBAJ}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n{{wikivoyage|Reynosa}}\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/6EjXaEdST?url=http://www.inegi.gob.mx/est/contenidos/espanol/sistemas/conteo2005/localidad/iter/ Link to tables of population data from Census of 2005] INEGI: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Geograf\u00eda e Inform\u00e1tica\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110517163702/http://www.e-local.gob.mx/wb2/ELOCAL/EMM_tamaulipas Tamaulipas] Enciclopedia de los Municipios de M\u00e9xico\n* [http://www.reynosa.gob.mx Gobierno de Reynosa]\n\n{{Tamaulipas}}\n\n[[Category:Reynosa| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:Mexico\u2013United States border crossings]]\n[[Category:Rio Grande Valley]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1749]]\n[[Category:1740s establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1749 establishments in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Reynosa\n|native_name            = <small>''Villa de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe de Reynosa''<small>\n|nickname               = Metr\u00f3polis industrial de Tamaulipas\n|motto                  = ''Trabajar por la patria es forjar nuestro destino''<br />(To work for the motherland is to forge our destiny)\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|image_seal             = Escudoreynosa.jpg\n|image_shield           =\n|image_map              = Reynosa, TM-map.svg\n|mapsize                = 150px\n|map_caption            = Location of Reynosa within Tamaulipas\n|image_map1             = Mexico map, MX-TAM.svg\n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = Location of Tamaulipas within Mexico\n|subdivision_type       = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Mexico}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[States of Mexico|State]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Tamaulipas}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Political divisions o