  = 33\n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = 88500\n|website                = [http://www.reynosa.gob.mx www.reynosa.gob.mx]\n|footnotes              = Area Code          899\n'''Airport'''  <br /> [[General Lucio Blanco International Airport]]\n'''Airport Code''' <br /> REX\n}}\n'''Reynosa''' ({{IPA-es|rei\u02c8nosa}}) is a border city in the northern part of the state of [[Tamaulipas]], in [[Mexico]]. It is also the municipal seat of [[Reynosa Municipality]].\n\nThe city is located on the southern bank of the [[Rio Grande]] in the international [[Reynosa\u2013McAllen Metropolitan Area]], directly across of the [[Mexico-U.S. border]] from [[Hidalgo, Texas]]. \n\nAs of 2013, the city of Reynosa has a population of 672,183.<ref name=\"Mexico Census\"/>   If the [[floating population]] is included in the census count, the population can reach up to approximately 1,000,000.<ref>{{cite news|title=INEGI cont\u00f3 mal en Reynosa: Alcalde|url=http://www.hoytamaulipas.net/notas/31372/INEGI-conto-mal-en-Reynosa-Alcalde.html|newspaper=Hoy Tamaulipas|date=4 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nReynosa was founded on 14 March 1749 with 297 inhabitants by Carlos Cant\u00fa under the command of [[Jos\u00e9 de Escand\u00f3n y Helguera]] the Count of [[Sierra Gorda]]. But due to flooding in the area on the 4 July 1802, they decided to move five miles to the east keeping the same margin between them and the Rio Grande. It was not until 1926 that the state government recognized Reynosa as a city.\n\nReynosa was first named ''Villa de Nuestra Se\u00f1ora de Guadalupe de Reinosa''. The pioneers of the Villa proceeded from El Nuevo Reino de Le\u00f3n, especially from Monterrey, Cadereyta, Cerralvo and El Pil\u00f3n. The town was composed of 50 families. It was given the name of Reynosa as a tribute to the [[Reinosa|town with the same name]] in Spain, the birthplace of the [[Viceroyalties of the Spanish Empire|Viceroy]] [[Juan Francisco de G\u00fcemes, 1st Count of Revillagigedo|de G\u00fcemes y Horcasitas]].\n\n===Current===\nReynosa extends across 3,156.34 sq kilometers (1218.66 sq. miles), representing 3.7 per cent of the [[Tamaulipas]] territory. Today it is the location of several satellite U.S. companies doing business to take advantage of low labor rates and industry incentives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cfomaquiladoras.org/serieglobalizacion.en.html |title=Four-part series on globalization |publisher=Cfomaquiladoras.org |accessdate=2012-02-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120222214105/http://www.cfomaquiladoras.org/serieglobalizacion.en.html |archive-date=2012-02-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 September 2012, an explosion at the nearby [[Pemex]] gas plant killed 30 and injured 46 people. Pemex Director Juan Jose Suarez said that there was \"no evidence that it was a deliberate incident, or some kind of attack\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican Tamaulipas state gas plant blast kills 26|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19645529|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=19 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico probes Pemex gas plant explosion which killed 26|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19655901|accessdate=20 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-19670668 | work=BBC News | title=Blast at Pemex gas plant in Mexico claims more lives | date=20 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, it was described as a major hotspot in the [[Mexican Drug War]], as a result of the internecine wars between the [[Gulf_Cartel|Gulf]] and [[Los Zetas]] drugs cartels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/world-us-canada-40755559/trump-s-wall-on-patrol-in-the-border-s-deadliest-town|title=US-Mexico border's most dangerous town|website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nReynosa is the largest and most populous city in the state of Tamaulipas, followed by [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas|Matamoros]], [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Ciudad Victoria]], [[Tampico]], and [[R\u00edo Bravo, Tamaulipas|R\u00edo Bravo]]. In addition, the international [[Reynosa\u2013McAllen Metropolitan Area]] counts with a population of 1,500,000 inhabitants,<ref>{{cite web|title=McAllen Overview|url=http://www.mcallen.org/Business-Community/McAllen-Overview|publisher=McAllen Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=America: metropolitan areas (McAllen-Reynosa)|url=http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=32&geo=-2&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&pt=a&va=x|publisher=World Gazetteer|accessdate=13 November 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001090654/http://world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&dat=32&geo=-2&srt=pnan&col=aohdq&pt=a&va=x|archivedate=2007-10-01}}</ref> making it the [[Metropolitan areas of Mexico|third largest metropolitan area]] in the Mexico\u2013U.S. border after [[San Diego\u2013Tijuana]] and [[El Paso\u2013Ju\u00e1rez]]. Reynosa is the [[List of cities in Mexico|30th largest city]] in Mexico and anchors the largest metropolitan area in Tamaulipas.\n\nIn 2011, Reynosa was the fastest growing city in the state of Tamaulipas, and was among the top five fastest growing cities in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|title=City of Hidalgo, Texas|url=http://www.hidalgotexas.com/cityprofile.pdf|publisher=Profile of Hidalgo, Texas|accessdate=3 November 2011}}</ref> \n\nThe city is about {{convert|11|mi|km}} south of [[McAllen, Texas]].<ref>Sanchez, Claudio. \"[https://www.npr.org/2014/09/11/347392083/child-migrants-settle-uneasily-in-the-big-easy Child Migrants Settle Uneasily In The Big Easy]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6bMCsr7w4?url=http://www.npr.org/2014/09/11/347392083/child-migrants-settle-uneasily-in-the-big-easy Archive]). [[National Public Radio]]. September 11, 2014. Retrieved on September 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nReynosa has a [[semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Bsh'') with short, mild winters and hot summers.<ref name=encmuc>{{cite web | url = http://www.e-local.gob.mx/work/templates/enciclo/EMM28tamaulipas/municipios/20832a.html | title = Cozumel | publisher = Secretar\u00eda de Gobernaci\u00f3n | work = Enciclopedia de los Municipios de M\u00e9xico | language = Spanish | accessdate = April 13, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nWinters are mild and dry with a January high of {{convert|22|C|F|0}} and a low of {{convert|11|C|F|0}} although temperatures can fall below {{convert|10|C|F|0}}.<ref name = encmuc /> Summers are hot with a July mean of {{convert|30|C|F|0}} and temperatures can exceed {{convert|40|C|F|0}} anytime from May until August.<ref name = encmuc/> The average annual precipitation is {{convert|452|mm|in|0}}, with most of it being concentrated in the summer months though the months May and June are the wettest. \n\n{{Weather box\n|width = auto\n|location = Reynosa (1951\u20132010)\n|single line = Yes\n|metric first = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 35.0\n|Feb record high C = 38.0\n|Mar record high C = 44.0\n|Apr record high C = 42.0\n|May record high C = 43.0\n|Jun record high C = 42.0\n|Jul record high C = 43.0\n|Aug record high C = 42.0\n|Sep record high C = 40.0\n|Oct record high C = 39.0\n|Nov record high C = 38.0\n|Dec record high C = 36.0\n|Jan high C = 21.9\n|Feb high C = 24.5\n|Mar high C = 29.1\n|Apr high C = 31.8\n|May high C = 34.3\n|Jun high C = 36.7\n|Jul high C = 36.9\n|Aug high C = 36.6\n|Sep high C = 35.0\n|Oct high C = 31.0\n|Nov high C = 26.7\n|Dec high C = 23.0\n|year high C = 30.6\n|Jan mean C = 16.2\n|Feb mean C = 18.4\n|Mar mean C = 21.9\n|Apr mean C = 24.8\n|May mean C = 27.6\n|Jun mean C = 29.5\n|Jul mean C = 29.9\n|Aug mean C = 29.8\n|Sep mean C = 28.1\n|Oct mean C = 24.6\n|Nov mean C = 20.6\n|Dec mean C = 17.3\n|year mean C = 24.1\n|Jan low C = 10.6\n|Feb low C = 12.3\n|Mar low C = 14.8\n|Apr low C = 17.7\n|May low C = 21.0\n|Jun low C = 22.2\n|Jul low C = 22.8\n|Aug low C = 23.0\n|Sep low C = 21.2\n|Oct low C = 18.3\n|Nov low C = 14.5\n|Dec low C = 11.6\n|year low C = 17.5\n|Jan record low C = -2.0\n|Feb record low C = -4.0\n|Mar record low C = 2.0\n|Apr record low C = 7.5\n|May record low C = 10.0\n|Jun record low C = 12.0\n|Jul record low C = 17.0\n|Aug record low C = 14.0\n|Sep record low C = 13.0\n|Oct record low C = 8.0\n|Nov record low C = 0.0\n|Dec record low C = -7.0\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 14.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 12.6\n|Mar precipitation mm = 7.3\n|Apr precipitation mm = 24.8\n|May precipitation mm = 73.0\n|Jun precipitation mm = 99.7\n|Jul precipitation mm = 24.3\n|Aug precipitation mm = 67.4\n|Sep precipitation mm = 72.6\n|Oct precipitation mm = 27.4\n|Nov precipitation mm = 11.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 16.9\n|year precipitation mm = 452.5\n|source 1 = Servicio Meteorologico Nacional<ref name=SMN>[http://smn.cna.gob.mx/climatologia/Normales5110/NORMAL28079.TXT NORMALES CLIMATOL\u00d3GICAS 1951\u20132010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517154247/http://smn.cna.gob.mx/climatologia/Normales5110/NORMAL28079.TXT |date=2014-05-17 }} (in Spanish) National Meteorological Service of Mexico. Retrieved September 30, 2012.</ref>\n|date=September 2012\n}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Abraham Ancer]] \u2013 Professional Golfer\n*[[Xavier Baez]] \u2013 Footballer\n*[[Jorge Cantu]] \u2013 Major League Baseball player\n*[[Christian Ch\u00e1vez]] \u2013 Singer and actor\n*[[Laura Flores]] \u2013 Actress, hostess and singer\n*[[Jaime Garc\u00eda (baseball)|Jaime Garcia]] \u2013 Major League Baseball player\n*[[N\u00e9stor Garza]] \u2013 Former WBA World Super Bantamweight Champion\n*[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Cant\u00fa Garza]] \u2013 Geneticist\n*[[Vidal Medina]] \u2013 Playwright and theatre director\n*[[Maki Esther Ortiz]] - Senator\n*[[Los Rel\u00e1mpagos del Norte]] - Musical duo\n*[[Komander]] - Wrestler\n*[[Ashty Edith Duncan]] - songwriter\n\n==Transportation==\nReynosa is served by the [[General Lucio Blanco International Airport]], which has flights to multiple important Mexican cities on six airlines, some serving it with aircraft such as [[Boeing 737]] and [[Airbus A320]].\n\nIn addition, the [[McAllen Miller International Airport]] in [[McAllen, Texas]], is also relatively close and is served by airlines like [[Allegiant Air]], [[American Airlines|American]] and [[United Airlines|United]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book|author=Broughton, Chad|title=Boom, Bust, Exodus: The Rust Belt, the Maquilas, and a Tale of Two Cities|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0199765614 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Boom_Bust_Exodus_The_Rust_Belt_the_Maqui.html?id=PWc3BQAAQBAJ}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n{{wikivoyage|Reynosa}}\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/6EjXaEdST?url=http://www.inegi.gob.mx/est/contenidos/espanol/sistemas/conteo2005/localidad/iter/ Link to tables of population data from Census of 2005] INEGI: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Geograf\u00eda e Inform\u00e1tica\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110517163702/http://www.e-local.gob.mx/wb2/ELOCAL/EMM_tamaulipas Tamaulipas] Enciclopedia de los Municipios de M\u00e9xico\n* [http://www.reynosa.gob.mx Gobierno de Reynosa]\n\n{{Tamaulipas}}\n\n[[Category:Reynosa| ]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Tamaulipas]]\n[[Category:Mexico\u2013United States border crossings]]\n[[Category:Rio Grande Valley]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1749]]\n[[Category:1740s establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1749 establishments in North America]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1702:1170:7240:57c:8461:3452:25e4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eNotable people)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reynosa"}
{"title_page": "A&W Root Beer", "text_new": "{{Short description|Root beer brand}}\n{{Infobox Beverage \n|name=A&W Root Beer\n|logo=A&W Root Beer logo.svg\n|image=\n|type=[[Root Beer]]\n|manufacturer=[[Keurig Dr Pepper]] (United States, Worldwide)<br/>[[A&W (Canada)|A&W Canada]], [[The Coca-Cola Company]] (Canada)\n|origin canada\n|introduced={{start date and age|1919}}\n|discontinued=\n|related=[[Barq's]], [[Mug Root Beer]], [[Dad's Root Beer]], [[Hires Root Beer]], [[A&W Cream Soda]]\n|variants= \n}}\n{{Infobox nutrition facts\n  | serv_size_us   = 8.1 fl oz\n  | serv_size_met  = 1 cup / 240 ml\n  | #_servings     = \n  | calories       = 120\n  | cal_from_fat   = 0\n  | total_fat_g    = 0\n  | sat_fat_g      = 0\n  | trans_fat_g    = 0\n  | cholesterol_mg = 0\n  | sodium_mg      = 30\n  | potassium_mg   = 0\n  | carb_g         = 31\n  | fiber_g        = 0\n  | sugars_g       = 31\n  | protein_g      = 0\n  | vit_a          = 0\n  | vit_c          = 0\n  | calcium        = 0\n  | iron           = 0\n}}\n{{Portal|Drink}}\n\n'''A&W Root Beer''' is a [[root beer]] brand primarily available in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]]. Founded in 1919 by [[Roy W. Allen]],<ref name=\"Site History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-12-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114141940/http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |archivedate=2008-01-14 }} \u2013 A&W root beer's official history</ref> Allen partnered with Frank Wright in 1922. They combined their initials to create the brand \"A&W\" and inspired a [[A&W Restaurants|restaurant chain]], also founded in 1922. Originally, A&W root beer drinks sold for five cents.<ref name=\"Keurig Dr Pepper Brands\">[http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/brands/aw/ Our Brands \u2013 Keurig Dr Pepper<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOutside Canada, the rights to the A&W brand are owned by [[Keurig Dr Pepper]], which in turn, licenses the brand to the similarly named U.S.-based restaurant chain; A&W products are distributed via various U.S. bottlers. [[A&W (Canada)|A&W Food Services of Canada]], which is independent of both Keurig Dr Pepper and the U.S. chain, is responsible for the restaurants and the marketing of root beer products in that country,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awincomefund.ca/aboutaw/default.asp |author=A&W Revenue Royalties Income Fund |title=About A&W Food Services of Canada Inc. |accessdate=2011-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706164821/http://www.awincomefund.ca/aboutaw/default.asp |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> with retail products bottled and distributed by [[The Coca-Cola Company]]. The U.S. variant is also sold as an import drink in [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Italy]] (where A&W has restaurants), as well as [[Australia]], and [[Chile]], among other countries.\n\n== History ==\n\nOn June 20, 1919, [[Roy W. Allen]] opened a roadside root beer stand in [[Lodi, California]], using a formula he had purchased from a pharmacist.<ref name=encyc>Smith, Andrew F., Encyclopedia of Junk Food and Fast Food, Greenwood Press, 2006. pp. 44\u201345.</ref> He soon opened stands in [[Stockton, California]], and five stands in nearby [[Sacramento]], home of the country's first [[drive-in]] featuring \"tray-boys\" for curbside service. In 1920, Allen became partners with Frank Wright and the two combined their initials and called their product A&W Root Beer. A mistaken notion is that the initials were derived from Alice and [[J. Willard Marriott|Willard Marriott]]. This mistake arose owing to Marriott's first business, an A&W franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html|title=The History of Root Beer}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, Allen bought Wright's share, obtained a trademark, and began selling restaurant [[Franchising|franchises]]. A&W was one of the first franchised [[Chain store|restaurant chains]] in the United States. Franchise owners could use the A&W name and logo and purchased concentrated root beer syrup from Allen. By 1933, there were more than 170 A&W franchised outlets. There was no common menu, architecture, or procedures shared by the franchisees and some chose to sell food with the root beer.<ref name=encyc/>\n\nFranchises struggled with labor shortages and sugar rationing during [[World War II]], but following the war, the number of A&W outlets tripled as GI loans paved the way for private enterprise. Driven by the popularity of the automobile and the new mobile society, more than 450 A&W Root Beer stands were operating by 1950. In that same year, Allen retired and sold the business to [[Nebraska]]n Gene Hurtz, who formed the A&W Root Beer Company. The first A&W Root Beer outlet in Canada opened in 1956.\n\nBy 1960, the number of A&W restaurants swelled to more than 2,000. In 1963, the A&W Root Beer Company was sold to the J. Hungerford Smith Company, which had produced Allen's concentrate since 1921. In the same year, the first overseas A&W restaurant opened its doors in [[Guam]].\n\nIn 1963, the company was sold to the [[United Fruit Company]], then renamed the [[Chiquita Brands International|United Brands Company]]. In 1971, United Brands formed a wholly owned subsidiary, A&W Distributing Co., for the purpose of making A&W Root Beer available in bottles on the grocery shelf. After a test run in [[Arizona]] and California, the products were distributed nationally in the United States, along with sugar-free, low-sodium, and caffeine-free versions. In 1974, A&W introduced \"The Great Root Bear,\" a mascot that served as a goodwill ambassador for the brand.\n\nIn the late 1970s, [[A&W Restaurants]] was formed to manage restaurant franchising. It was bought in 1982 by [[A. Alfred Taubman]].\n\nThe bear and the tuba jingle that accompanied him became a long-running campaign (the tune, entitled \"Ba-Dum, Ba-Dum\", was released as a single by Attic Records, credited to \"Major Ursus\", a play on Ursa Major or \"great bear\"). The famous Canadian composer and B.C. Hall of Fame winner Robert Buckley helped compose the song. The mascot was so successful that he was eventually adopted as the mascot by the American A&W chain as well. The famous tuba jingle was played by famed Vancouver jazz, classical and session trombonist Sharman King. King also did the ads for the \"Book Warehouse\" chain of discount book stores, which he owned.\n\nIn 1986, A&W Cream Soda and A&W Diet Cream Soda were introduced and distributed nationally, followed in 1987 by the reformulation of sugar-free A&W as Diet A&W.\n\nIn October 1993, A&W Beverages was folded into [[Cadbury plc|Cadbury]] Beverages. That company would spin off its US beverages business as [[Keurig Dr Pepper]] in 2008.\n\nIn March 2005, A&W began to appear in the Vintage Bottle, a 20-ounce bottle with graphics reminiscent of an old fashioned root beer barrel. The brand's current tagline is, \"Classic American Refreshment Since 1919.\"\n\nIn July 2017, A&W Canada reformulated its root beer, dropping [[High Fructose Corn Syrup]] and some flavors from the recipe, substituting [[cane sugar]], sarsaparilla root, [[licorice]], [[birch bark]], and [[anise]]. They launched the new formula by declaring Free Root Beer Day, serving free A&W Root Beer at all locations across the country from open to close on Saturday July 22, 2017.<ref name=\"NaturalA&Wcanada\">{{cite web |title=A&W Canada is brewing root beer with natural ingredients |url=http://awincomefund.mediaroom.com/2017-07-05-A-W-Canada-is-brewing-root-beer-with-natural-ingredients |publisher=[[A&W (Canada)|A&W Food Services of Canada]] |accessdate=5 January 2019 |date=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Brands ==\n\n* A&W Sugar-free Root Beer was introduced in 1974,<ref name=\"Site History\"/> and reformulated as Diet A&W in 1987.<ref name=\"Site History\"/>\n* [[A&W Cream Soda]] and Diet Cream Soda were introduced in 1986.<ref name=\"Site History\"/>\n*[[Floats (drink)|A&W Float]]s and [[Floats (drink)|Sunkist Float]]s were introduced in 2008.\n*A&W TEN, a low calorie root beer, began appearing in American supermarkets in the spring of 2013.\n\n== Promotions and contests ==\n* A&W and [[Jim Belushi]] offered a trip to Los Angeles with a [[Very Important Person|VIP]] pass to \"A&W Ultimate All-American Cookout and Concert\" at the [[House of Blues]], via [[eBay]].<ref name=highbeam>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131706656.html eBay Bidders Can Vie for Trip to A&W Root Beer's 'Ultimate All-American Cookout and Concert' Featuring Jim Belushi and The Sacred Hearts Band; Proceeds From Online Charity Auction to Benefit John Belushi Scholarship Fund. \u2013 PR Newswire \u2013 HighBeam Research<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n*In celebration of their 100th anniversary, A&W offered a free 2-liter bottle of A&W Root Beer in exchange for a pledge called \"The Family Fun Pledge\" which asked participants to be \"technology-free for one hour every Friday night this summer.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Pledge to go Technology-Free and Create Family Fun with A&W Root Beer |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pledge-to-go-technology-free-and-create-family-fun-with-aw-root-beer-300860669.html |website=www.prnewswire.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The Great Root Bear ==\n[[File:Avenue du Mont-Royal 07a.JPG|thumbnail|upright|<center>Rooty, the Great Root Bear</center>]]\nThe '''Great Root Bear''', also called Rooty, is the mascot for A&W Root Beer. It was first used in 1974 by [[A&W (Canada)|Canada's ''A&W'']], and was adopted by the American chain in 1976. In a long-running television advertising campaign for the Canadian A&W chain, his theme was a tuba-driven jingle entitled \"Ba-Dum, Ba-Dum\" and released as a single by [[Attic Records (Canada)|Attic Records]] in Canada, credited to \"Major Ursus\", a play on the constellation name [[Ursa Major]], which means \"great bear\". The famous Canadian composer and B.C. Hall of Fame winner Robert Buckley helped compose the song. In the late 1990s, the Great Root Bear's role as mascot was reduced for the restaurant chain, ultimately replaced by \"The Burger Family\", although it still appeared in various capacities for the restaurants and on A&W Root Beer cases in Canada.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}} In late 2011, the new ownership of A&W began using the mascot again, particularly in A&W's online presence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sloan |first=Scott |url=http://www.kentucky.com/2013/04/14/2600564/aw-brings-back-its-official-spokesbear.html |title=A&W brings back its official spokesbear, Rooty &#124; Daily Business Report |publisher=Kentucky.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== A&W Restaurants ==\n{{main|A&W Restaurants|A&W (Canada)}}\n[[File:A&W Logo.svg|thumbnail|upright|A&W Restaurants logo]]\n\nShortly after Allen bought out Wright's portion of the business, he began franchising the product. His [[Profit (accounting)|profits]] came from a small franchise fee and sales of concentrate. There was no standard food [[menu]] for franchises until 1978. By 1960, they had 2,000 [[retail stores|stores]].\n\nIn 1989, A&W made an agreement with [[Minnesota]]-based chain Carousel Snack Bars to convert that chain's 200 locations (mostly kiosks in shopping malls) to \"A&W Hot Dogs & More\".<ref>[http://www.awrootbeer.com/hist_hist3.htm A&W Root Beer&nbsp;\u2014 History & Collectables] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128035003/http://www.awrootbeer.com/hist_hist3.htm |date=November 28, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_n17_v25/ai_10659563 A&W prexy sets pace for growth in the '90's&nbsp;\u2014 A&W Restaurants; George Michel]</ref> Some A&W Hot Dogs & More locations are in operation today.\n\nMany A&W locations that opened in the U.S. during the Yum! Brands ownership years (2002\u20132011) were co-branded with Yum!'s other chains\u2014[[Long John Silver's]], [[Taco Bell]], [[Pizza Hut]], or [[KFC]].\n\nAs of December 2011, A&W was bought by new ownership and their World Headquarters moved back to [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. Since then, in the United States and Southeast Asia, A&W has been a franchisee-owned company.<ref>[https://www.awrestaurants.com/franchise-opportunities Franchise Opportunities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611132845/http://www.awrestaurants.com/franchise-opportunities |date=2015-06-11 }} A & W Restaurants.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeer.com/history |title=A&W Root Beer&nbsp;\u2014 History |accessdate=2008-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827210543/http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |archivedate=2008-08-27 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.rootbeer.com A&W's root beer site]\n* [http://www.gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html The History of Root Beer]\n* [http://www.rootbeerbarrel.com/ Root Beer Reviews and info]\n\n{{Root beer brands}}\n{{Coca-Cola}}\n{{Keurig Dr Pepper brands}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:AandW Root Beer}}\n[[Category:Root beer]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 1919]]\n[[Category:Keurig Dr Pepper brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Root beer brand}}\n{{Infobox Beverage \n|name=A&W Root Beer\n|logo=A&W Root Beer logo.svg\n|image=\n|type=[[Root Beer]]\n|manufacturer=[[Keurig Dr Pepper]] (United States, Worldwide)<br/>[[A&W (Canada)|A&W Canada]], [[The Coca-Cola Company]] (Canada)\n|origin canada\n|introduced={{start date and age|1919}}\n|discontinued=\n|related=[[Barq's]], [[Mug Root Beer]], [[Dad's Root Beer]], [[Hires Root Beer]], [[A&W Cream Soda]]\n|variants= \n}}\n{{Infobox nutrition facts\n  | serv_size_us   = 8.1 fl oz\n  | serv_size_met  = 1 cup / 240 ml\n  | #_servings     = \n  | calories       = 120\n  | cal_from_fat   = 0\n  | total_fat_g    = 0\n  | sat_fat_g      = 0\n  | trans_fat_g    = 0\n  | cholesterol_mg = 0\n  | sodium_mg      = 30\n  | potassium_mg   = 0\n  | carb_g         = 31\n  | fiber_g        = 0\n  | sugars_g       = 31\n  | protein_g      = 0\n  | vit_a          = 0\n  | vit_c          = 0\n  | calcium        = 0\n  | iron           = 0\n}}\n{{Portal|Drink}}\n\n'''A&W Root Beer''' is a [[root beer]] brand primarily available in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]]. Founded in 1919 by [[Roy W. Allen]],<ref name=\"Site History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-12-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114141940/http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |archivedate=2008-01-14 }} \u2013 A&W root beer's official history</ref> Allen partnered with Frank Wright in 1922. They combined their initials to create the brand \"A&W\" and inspired a [[A&W Restaurants|restaurant chain]], also founded in 1922. Originally, A&W root beer drinks sold for five cents.<ref name=\"Keurig Dr Pepper Brands\">[http://www.drpeppersnapplegroup.com/brands/aw/ Our Brands \u2013 Keurig Dr Pepper<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOutside Canada, the rights to the A&W brand are owned by [[Keurig Dr Pepper]], which in turn, licenses the brand to the similarly named U.S.-based restaurant chain; A&W products are distributed via various U.S. bottlers. [[A&W (Canada)|A&W Food Services of Canada]], which is independent of both Keurig Dr Pepper and the U.S. chain, is responsible for the restaurants and the marketing of root beer products in that country,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awincomefund.ca/aboutaw/default.asp |author=A&W Revenue Royalties Income Fund |title=About A&W Food Services of Canada Inc. |accessdate=2011-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706164821/http://www.awincomefund.ca/aboutaw/default.asp |archivedate=2011-07-06 }}</ref> with retail products bottled and distributed by [[The Coca-Cola Company]]. The U.S. variant is also sold as an import drink in [[Southeast Asia]] and [[Italy]] (where A&W has restaurants), as well as [[Australia]], and [[Chile]], among other countries.\n\n== History ==\n\nOn June 20, 1919, [[Roy W. Allen]] opened a roadside root beer stand in [[Lodi, California]], using a formula he had purchased from a pharmacist.<ref name=encyc>Smith, Andrew F., Encyclopedia of Junk Food and Fast Food, Greenwood Press, 2006. pp. 44\u201345.</ref> He soon opened stands in [[Stockton, California]], and five stands in nearby [[Sacramento]], home of the country's first [[drive-in]] featuring \"tray-boys\" for curbside service. In 1920, Allen became partners with Frank Wright and the two combined their initials and called their product A&W Root Beer. A mistaken notion is that the initials were derived from Alice and [[J. Willard Marriott|Willard Marriott]]. This mistake arose owing to Marriott's first business, an A&W franchise<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gourmetrootbeer.com/history.html|title=The History of Root Beer}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, Allen bought Wright's share, obtained a trademark, and began selling restaurant [[Franchising|franchises]]. A&W was one of the first franchised [[Chain store|restaurant chains]] in the United States. Franchise owners could use the A&W name and logo and purchased concentrated root beer syrup from Allen. By 1933, there were more than 170 A&W franchised outlets. There was no common menu, architecture, or procedures shared by the franchisees and some chose to sell food with the root beer.<ref name=encyc/>\n\nFranchises struggled with labor shortages and sugar rationing during [[World War II]], but following the war, the number of A&W outlets tripled as GI loans paved the way for private enterprise. Driven by the popularity of the automobile and the new mobile society, more than 450 A&W Root Beer stands were operating by 1950. In that same year, Allen retired and sold the business to [[Nebraska]]n Gene Hurtz, who formed the A&W Root Beer Company. The first A&W Root Beer outlet in Canada opened in 1956.\n\nBy 1960, the number of A&W restaurants swelled to more than 2,000. In 1963, the A&W Root Beer Company was sold to the J. Hungerford Smith Company, which had produced Allen's concentrate since 1921. In the same year, the first overseas A&W restaurant opened its doors in [[Guam]].\n\nIn 1963, the company was sold to the [[United Fruit Company]], then renamed the [[Chiquita Brands International|United Brands Company]]. In 1971, United Brands formed a wholly owned subsidiary, A&W Distributing Co., for the purpose of making A&W Root Beer available in bottles on the grocery shelf. After a test run in [[Arizona]] and California, the products were distributed nationally in the United States, along with sugar-free, low-sodium, and caffeine-free versions. In 1974, A&W introduced \"The Great Root Bear,\" a mascot that served as a goodwill ambassador for the brand.\n\nIn the late 1970s, [[A&W Restaurants]] was formed to manage restaurant franchising. It was bought in 1982 by [[A. Alfred Taubman]].\n\nThe bear and the tuba jingle that accompanied him became a long-running campaign (the tune, entitled \"Ba-Dum, Ba-Dum\", was released as a single by Attic Records, credited to \"Major Ursus\", a play on Ursa Major or \"great bear\"). The famous Canadian composer and B.C. Hall of Fame winner Robert Buckley helped compose the song. The mascot was so successful that he was eventually adopted as the mascot by the American A&W chain as well. The famous tuba jingle was played by famed Vancouver jazz, classical and session trombonist Sharman King. King also did the ads for the \"Book Warehouse\" chain of discount book stores, which he owned.\n\nIn 1986, A&W Cream Soda and A&W Diet Cream Soda were introduced and distributed nationally, followed in 1987 by the reformulation of sugar-free A&W as Diet A&W.\n\nIn October 1993, A&W Beverages was folded into [[Cadbury plc|Cadbury]] Beverages. That company would spin off its US beverages business as [[Keurig Dr Pepper]] in 2008.\n\nIn March 2005, A&W began to appear in the Vintage Bottle, a 20-ounce bottle with graphics reminiscent of an old fashioned root beer barrel. The brand's current tagline is, \"Classic American Refreshment Since 1919.\"\n\nIn July 2017, A&W Canada reformulated its root beer, dropping [[High Fructose Corn Syrup]] and some flavors from the recipe, substituting [[cane sugar]], sarsaparilla root, [[licorice]], [[birch bark]], and [[anise]]. They launched the new formula by declaring Free Root Beer Day, serving free A&W Root Beer at all locations across the country from open to close on Saturday July 22, 2017.<ref name=\"NaturalA&Wcanada\">{{cite web |title=A&W Canada is brewing root beer with natural ingredients |url=http://awincomefund.mediaroom.com/2017-07-05-A-W-Canada-is-brewing-root-beer-with-natural-ingredients |publisher=[[A&W (Canada)|A&W Food Services of Canada]] |accessdate=5 January 2019 |date=5 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Brands ==\n\n* A&W Sugar-free Root Beer was introduced in 1974,<ref name=\"Site History\"/> and reformulated as Diet A&W in 1987.<ref name=\"Site History\"/>\n* [[A&W Cream Soda]] and Diet Cream Soda were introduced in 1986.<ref name=\"Site History\"/>\n*[[Floats (drink)|A&W Float]]s and [[Floats (drink)|Sunkist Float]]s were introduced in 2008.\n*A&W TEN, a low calorie root beer, began appearing in American supermarkets in the spring of 2013.\n\n== Promotions and contests ==\n* A&W and [[Jim Belushi]] offered a trip to Los Angeles with a [[Very Important Person|VIP]] pass to \"A&W Ultimate All-American Cookout and Concert\" at the [[House of Blues]], via [[eBay]].<ref name=highbeam>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131706656.html eBay Bidders Can Vie for Trip to A&W Root Beer's 'Ultimate All-American Cookout and Concert' Featuring Jim Belushi and The Sacred Hearts Band; Proceeds From Online Charity Auction to Benefit John Belushi Scholarship Fund. \u2013 PR Newswire \u2013 HighBeam Research<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n*In celebration of their 100th anniversary, A&W offered a free 2-liter bottle of A&W Root Beer in exchange for a pledge called \"The Family Fun Pledge\" which asked participants to be \"technology-free for one hour every Friday night this summer.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Pledge to go Technology-Free and Create Family Fun with A&W Root Beer |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pledge-to-go-technology-free-and-create-family-fun-with-aw-root-beer-300860669.html |website=www.prnewswire.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n== The Great Root Bear ==\n[[File:Avenue du Mont-Royal 07a.JPG|thumbnail|upright|<center>Rooty, the Great Root Bear</center>]]\nThe '''Great Root Bear''', also called Rooty, is the mascot for A&W Root Beer. It was first used in 1974 by [[A&W (Canada)|Canada's ''A&W'']], and was adopted by the American chain in 1976. In a long-running television advertising campaign for the Canadian A&W chain, his theme was a tuba-driven jingle entitled \"Ba-Dum, Ba-Dum\" and released as a single by [[Attic Records (Canada)|Attic Records]] in Canada, credited to \"Major Ursus\", a play on the constellation name [[Ursa Major]], which means \"great bear\". The famous Canadian composer and B.C. Hall of Fame winner Robert Buckley helped compose the song. In the late 1990s, the Great Root Bear's role as mascot was reduced for the restaurant chain, ultimately replaced by \"The Burger Family\", although it still appeared in various capacities for the restaurants and on A&W Root Beer cases in Canada.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}} In late 2011, the new ownership of A&W began using the mascot again, particularly in A&W's online presence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sloan |first=Scott |url=http://www.kentucky.com/2013/04/14/2600564/aw-brings-back-its-official-spokesbear.html |title=A&W brings back its official spokesbear, Rooty &#124; Daily Business Report |publisher=Kentucky.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-30}}</ref>\n\n== A&W Restaurants ==\n{{main|A&W Restaurants|A&W (Canada)}}\n[[File:A&W Logo.svg|thumbnail|upright|A&W Restaurants logo]]\n\nShortly after Allen bought out Wright's portion of the business, he began franchising the product. His [[Profit (accounting)|profits]] came from a small franchise fee and sales of concentrate. There was no standard food [[menu]] for franchises until 1978. By 1960, they had 2,000 [[retail stores|stores]].\n\nIn 1989, A&W made an agreement with [[Minnesota]]-based chain Carousel Snack Bars to convert that chain's 200 locations (mostly kiosks in shopping malls) to \"A&W Hot Dogs & More\".<ref>[http://www.awrootbeer.com/hist_hist3.htm A&W Root Beer&nbsp;\u2014 History & Collectables] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071128035003/http://www.awrootbeer.com/hist_hist3.htm |date=November 28, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3190/is_n17_v25/ai_10659563 A&W prexy sets pace for growth in the '90's&nbsp;\u2014 A&W Restaurants; George Michel]</ref> Some A&W Hot Dogs & More locations are in operation today.\n\nMany A&W locations that opened in the U.S. during the Yum! Brands ownership years (2002\u20132011) were co-branded with Yum!'s other chains\u2014[[Long John Silver's]], [[Taco Bell]], [[Pizza Hut]], or [[KFC]].\n\nAs of December 2011, A&W was bought by new ownership and their World Headquarters moved back to [[Lexington, Kentucky]]. Since then, in the United States and Southeast Asia, A&W has been a franchisee-owned company.<ref>[https://www.awrestaurants.com/franchise-opportunities Franchise Opportunities] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611132845/http://www.awrestaurants.com/franchise-opportunities |date=2015-06-11 }} A & W Restaurants.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.rootbeer.com/history |title=A&W Root Beer&nbsp;\u2014 History |accessdate=2008-10-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827210543/http://www.rootbeer.com/history/ |arc